## What level 7 turned out to be

A remix of the level-6 combination-lock family, hidden behind a **fog-of-war diamond** centered on the avatar (radius ≈ energy bar / 2), which makes blind BFS hopeless — the map, buttons and lock room are all invisible from the start.

Discovered by clone experiments:
- **Fog + energy**: every move drains the bar 2; boxes (3×3 colour-11 rings) set it to 42; bar 0 = death/reset. Vision shrinks with energy.
- **Mapping**: stitched the full maze from clone tours, distrusting wall pixels near the fog edge (the edge is drawn in wall colour).
- **Buttons are static now**: creature tile (40,9) = colour+1 per entry; digit-sprite tile (40,19) = the level-6 "A" 6-cycle per entry. Only the right-corridor sprite patrols (col 56, 1 tile/tick) and fires the rotation **R** each time it crosses the avatar.
- **Springs** (pip-marked, one-way, verified): (20,39)→(40,39), (30,39)→(30,29), (30,34)→(10,34).
- **The lock**: single room at tile (50,29) with pattern R²(S0) in colour 8; pressing from (45,29) succeeds only on display match (wrong press = free no-op).

Winning word: **C³ A⁵ R²**, ordered C,A first (bottom-left buttons), then R by bouncing in the patroller's corridor with display feedback, then spring back straight onto the room approach — with four box refuels. An offline adaptive controller derived a deterministic 65-move path, verified by pure replay.

`play_level_7` composes the existing `solve_by_replay` leg (same shape as levels 5–6; no new leg needed since the game is deterministic), the checkpoint was extended to the validated 393-move path, and the debrief was logged in `legs_log.md`.
